      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. It's often described as a \"spooky action at a distance,\" a phrase Einstein famously used to express his discomfort with the idea.\n\nTo understand how it differs from classical correlation, imagine you have two coins. If you flip them and they always land on heads, that's a classical correlation because you could have simply pre-agreed on the outcome before flipping them. In quantum mechanics, however, the particles don't have a definite state until they are measured. When you measure one entangled particle, the other instantly \"collapses\" into the corresponding state, even if it's light-years away. This isn't just about shared information; it's a fundamental connection that defies our classical intuition of local realism.\n\nThink of it like this: in the classical world, two friends might wear matching socks because they bought a pair together. In the quantum world, two particles are like two tiny, invisible, magical twins who share a single existence. If one twin puts on a red sock, the other instantly knows and puts on a red sock,",
      "source": "target",
